</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B5E217BCE5112523D74F941FBCBF89E" blockId="13.[264,1322,1513,1899]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Comments. This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="FCE15AF8CE5112523F72F941FAC4F97E" authority="Yang and Saigusa" authorityName="Yang and Saigusa" box="[830,1322,1673,1699]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Chrysotimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unifascia">
<emphasis id="0995FD69CE5112523F72F941FBA6F97F" box="[830,1096,1673,1698]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Chrysotimus unifascia</emphasis>
Yang and Saigusa
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion id="F925EF99CE5112523D05F979FE44F916" box="[329,426,1713,1739]" country="China" name="Shaanxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Shaanxi</collectingRegion>
, but may be separated from the latter by hind tarsomere 1 with 10–12 erect short black ventral bristles on basal 1/5, and epandrium narrowing to apex, surstylus narrow. In 
<taxonomicName id="FCE15AF8CE5112523D2AF8C9FE1BF8C7" box="[358,501,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Chrysotimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unifascia">
<emphasis id="0995FD69CE5112523D2AF8C9FE1BF8C7" box="[358,501,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. unifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the hind tarsomere 1 has 4–5 short black ventral bristles, and epandrium is round apically, surstylus is thick (
<bibRefCitation id="5F705C8ACE5112523EB4F8E1FBF6F89E" author="Yang, D. &amp; Saigusa, T." box="[760,1048,1833,1859]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="740 - 765" refId="ref12105" refString="Yang, D. &amp; Saigusa, T. (2005) Diptera: Dolichopodidae. In: Yang, X. (Ed.), Insect Fauna of Middle-West Qinling Range and South Mountains of Gansu Province. Science Press, Beijing, pp. 740 - 765." type="book chapter" year="2005">Yang and Saigusa, 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
